\subsubsection{FLAPW}





\textcolor{Sepia}{Stationary DFT gives results that have a good interpretation of the experimental data and apparently well describes the energy levels. It becomes interesting to consider electronic transitions between zones in dynamics under the action of a certain perturbation. For this purpose, the extension of stationary DFT to time-dependent is introduced in next chapter.}


\subsection{TD-CCM-DFT equations}

The analogous statement to that of Hohenberg and Kohn is the Runge-Gross theorem. Its proof is more elaborate, since no minimization principle can be applied on the quantum-mechanical action, but only a condition of extremalization. The theorem states a one-to-one correspondence – up to a time-dependent function c(t) – between the external potential V (r, t) and the density n(r, t) now both being time-dependent:
\begin{eqnarray}
equation \: 2.48\: (Manfred \: Niesert)
\label{_21}
\end{eqnarray}
Analogously to (2.17) this means that also in the time-dependent setting the external potential as well as the Hamiltonian, the many-body states or any observable can be considered as a functional of the density n. It is important to realize that in this time-dependent framework this means that these quantities are functionals of the density in the whole space and the current time as well as all past times. This is important since one can construct two systems which have identical densities and external potentials  in the whole space and for a given time t, but propagate differently for future times. Therefore identical densities and external potentials for one given time are not sufficient; instead identical densities and potentials have to be ensured for all past times as well.

Consequently, one-particle orbitals can be constructed in the spirit of Kohn and Sham, which in the collinear case are related to the density by
\begin{eqnarray}
equation \: 2.49\: (Manfred \: Niesert)
\label{_22}
\end{eqnarray}
and are determined by the time-dependent Kohn-Sham equations:
\begin{eqnarray}
equation \: 2.50\: (Manfred \: Niesert)
\label{_23}
\end{eqnarray}
The external contribution to the now time-dependent effective potential
\begin{eqnarray}
equation \: 2.51\: (Manfred \: Niesert)
\label{_24}
\end{eqnarray}
takes up the external field newly added in TDDFT, as does the external contribution to the effective magnetic field
\begin{eqnarray}
equation \: 2.52\: (Manfred \: Niesert)
\label{_24}
\end{eqnarray}
The exchange-correlation functional now depends on the density and magnetization in the whole space at all past times. The potential and magnetic field could naively be defined in analogy to conventional DFT as functional derivatives of the quantum-mechanical action with respect to the density and magnetization. However, the exchange-correlation potential now memorizes the development of the system in time, provoking a problem related to causality. This theoretical issue was resolved by van Leeuwen [van98] using the Keldysh formalism, leading to an alternative action functional Ã[n, m] that the derivatives are applied on.

While this general statement about E xc completes the theoretical framework of TDDFT, the exchange-correlation potentials are still unknown but nevertheless as crucial for practical applications as they are in conventional DFT. The easiest and most apparent approximation is the use of $adiabatic$ functionals, i.e., the functionals from common DFT are evaluated with the time-dependent density:
\begin{eqnarray}
equation \: 2.53\: (Manfred \: Niesert)
\label{_24}
\end{eqnarray}
This makes the functional local in time, which is a quite drastic approximation, but also avoids the causality problem mentioned above. Since $V_{xc}^{DFT}$ is derived as a ground-state property, we can expect this to work only in cases where the temporal dependence is small and the time-dependent system is locally close to equilibrium. The particular use of the LDA functional in the TDDFT framework is commonly denoted as TDLDA or adiabatic LDA (ALDA).

The time-dependent DFT excels in particular in the computation of finite systems, however, also applications to solids are very promising. Due to its efficiency compared to the formalism of many-body perturbation theory, it is one of the premier tools to employ.

\textcolor{magenta}{[from  thesis Manfred Niesert]}


\textcolor{Sepia}{ There is an alternative way to describe non linear spin dynamics, which we will discuss in the next chapter. To do this, we rewrite the equations TD-DFT as seven equations with three variables. These variables are charge, current, and magnetization.}


\subsection{Equations for n,j,m}

Let a time dependent perturbation $\mathcal{V}\left( t\right) $ superimposes
the LSDF theory hamiltonian $\mathcal{H}$. Let us present fermion field
operators in the form
\begin{equation}
\psi _{\alpha }\left( \mathbf{r}\right) =\sum_{\nu }a_{v\alpha }\psi
_{v\alpha }\left( \mathbf{r}\right)  \label{Psi}
\end{equation}
where $\psi _{v\alpha }\left( \mathbf{r}\right) $ are Kohn-Sham
eigenfunctions, considered above, and $a_{v\alpha }$ is the fermion
annihilation operator. Then using well-known relation
\begin{equation*}
\left\langle A\right\rangle ^{t}=\text{Tr}\left[ \rho \left( t\right) A
\right] =\text{Tr}\left[ \rho \left( 0\right) A\left( t\right) \right]
\end{equation*}
where $\rho \left( t\right) $ is the nonequilibrium statistical operator and
\begin{equation}
\frac{dA\left( t\right) }{dt}=\frac{i}{\hbar }\left[ \mathcal{H}+\mathcal{V}
\left( t\right) ,A\left( t\right) \right] ,\;A\left( 0\right) =0.
\label{HeisEoM}
\end{equation}
Assuming that at $t\leq 0$ the system is at equilibrium, that is $\mathcal{V}
\left( t\right) =0$ and
\begin{equation*}
\rho \left( 0\right) =f\left( \mathcal{H}\right)
\end{equation*}
where $f\left( \varepsilon \right) $ is the Fermi function, we obtain
\begin{equation*}
n\left( \mathbf{r},t\right) =\sum_{\nu \alpha }f\left( \varepsilon _{\nu
\alpha }\right) n_{\nu \alpha }\left( \mathbf{r},t\right) ,\;\mathbf{m}
\left( \mathbf{r},t\right) =\sum_{\nu \alpha }f\left( \varepsilon _{\nu
\alpha }\right) \mathbf{m}_{\nu \alpha }\left( \mathbf{r},t\right)
\end{equation*}
where
\begin{eqnarray}
n_{\nu \alpha }\left( \mathbf{r},t\right) &=&\psi _{\underline{\beta }
;v\alpha }^{\ast }\left( \mathbf{r},t\right) \psi _{\underline{\beta }
;v\alpha }\left( \mathbf{r},t\right)  \label{pdensity1} \\
\mathbf{m}_{\nu \alpha }\left( \mathbf{r},t\right) &=&\psi _{\underline{
\beta };v\alpha }^{\ast }\left( \mathbf{r},t\right) \mathbf{\sigma }_{
\underline{\beta }\underline{\gamma }}\psi _{\underline{\gamma };v\alpha
}\left( \mathbf{r},t\right)  \label{sdensity1}
\end{eqnarray}
and $\psi _{\underline{\beta };v\alpha }\left( \mathbf{r},t\right) $ is the
solution to one-particle perturbed Schroedinger equation with the initial
condition
\begin{equation*}
\psi _{\underline{\beta };v\alpha }\left( \mathbf{r},0\right) =\psi
_{v\alpha }\left( \mathbf{r}\right) .
\end{equation*}
So Eqs.(\ref{pdensity1}) and (\ref{sdensity1}) are quasicalssical analogs of
Eqs.(\ref{pdensity}) and (\ref{sdensity}) respectively. Introducing also the
velocity vector function
\begin{equation}
\mathbf{v}_{\nu a}\left( \mathbf{r},t\right) =\frac{\hbar ^{2}}{2mi}\left( 
\frac{\psi _{\underline{\beta };v\alpha }^{\ast }\left( \mathbf{r},t\right) 
\mathbf{\nabla }\psi _{\underline{\beta };v\alpha }\left( \mathbf{r}
,t\right) }{n_{\nu \alpha }\left( \mathbf{r},t\right) }-\text{c.c.}\right)
\label{velocity}
\end{equation}
we are able to obtain closed system of non linear equations for the
functions $n_{\nu \alpha }\left( \mathbf{r},t\right) $, $\mathbf{m}_{\nu
\alpha }\left( \mathbf{r},t\right) $ and $\mathbf{v}_{\nu a}\left( \mathbf{r}
,t\right) $ derived by Takabayasi in 1955 (check see in papers). They have
the form (index of initial state is temporarily omitted)
\begin{equation}
\frac{\partial n}{\partial t}+\partial _{\underline{k}}\left( v_{\underline{k
}}n\right) =0  \label{denseq}
\end{equation}
\begin{equation}
\frac{\partial v_{i}}{\partial t}+v_{\underline{k}}\partial _{\underline{k}
}v_{i}=-\frac{1}{m}\partial _{i}\left( e\varphi +V_{\text{q}}\right) +\frac{1
}{m}\frac{\mathbf{m}}{n}\cdot \partial _{i}\mathbf{B}-\frac{1}{mn}\partial _{
\underline{k}}T_{\underline{k}i}  \label{veloceq}
\end{equation}
\begin{equation}
\frac{\partial \mathbf{m}}{\partial t}+\partial _{\underline{k}}\left( v_{
\underline{k}}\mathbf{m}\right) =\frac{1}{\hbar }\left( \mathbf{m\times B}
\right) +\frac{\hbar }{2m}\partial _{\underline{k}}\frac{1}{n}\left( \mathbf{
m}\times \partial _{\underline{k}}\mathbf{m}\right)  \label{momeq}
\end{equation}
where
\begin{equation}
V_{\text{q}}=\frac{\hbar ^{2}}{4m}\left( \frac{1}{2}\left\vert \frac{\mathbf{
\nabla }n}{n}\right\vert ^{2}-\frac{\triangle n}{n}\right)
\label{qpotential}
\end{equation}
is the `quantum' potential energy and
\begin{equation}
T_{ki}=T_{ik}=\frac{\hbar ^{2}}{4m}n\partial _{i}\left( \frac{\mathbf{m}}{n}
\right) \cdot \partial _{k}\left( \frac{\mathbf{m}}{n}\right)
\label{stensor}
\end{equation}
is the `magnetic' stress tensor. These equations are not all indepenent. We
have two constraints imposed on those variables
\begin{eqnarray}
n &=&\mathbf{m}\cdot \mathbf{m}  \label{constr1} \\
\mathbf{\nabla }\times \mathbf{v} &\mathbf{=}&\frac{\hbar }{2m}\mathbf{
\nabla }\left( \frac{m_{z}}{n}\right) \times \frac{m_{y}\mathbf{\nabla }
m_{x}-m_{x}\mathbf{\nabla }m_{y}}{m_{x}^{2}+m_{y}^{2}}  \label{constr2}
\end{eqnarray}
Also we have Poisson equation
\begin{equation}
\triangle \varphi _{\text{Coul}}=-4\pi e\left\langle n-n^{0}\right\rangle
\label{Poisson}
\end{equation}
and Stoner equation
\begin{equation}
\mathbf{B}_{\text{xc}}=B_{\text{xc}}\frac{\left\langle \mathbf{m}
\right\rangle }{\left\vert \left\langle \mathbf{m}\right\rangle \right\vert }
\label{Stoner}
\end{equation}
Let us recall that
\begin{equation}
\left\langle \mathbf{m}\right\rangle =\sum_{\nu \sigma }f\left( \varepsilon
_{\nu \sigma }\right) \mathbf{m}_{\nu \sigma },\;\left\langle n\right\rangle
=\sum_{\nu \sigma }f\left( \varepsilon _{\nu \sigma }\right) n_{\nu \sigma }
\label{means}
\end{equation}
etc. In equilibrium
\begin{eqnarray}
\mathbf{m}_{\nu \sigma } &=&\left( 0,0,\sigma n_{\nu \sigma }^{0}\right)
,\;T_{ik}=0,  \label{equistatemT} \\
\mathbf{\nabla }\times \mathbf{v}_{\nu \sigma } &=&0,\;\mathbf{B}=\left(
0,0,B_{\text{xt}}^{0}+B_{\text{xc}}^{0}\right)  \label{equistatevB}
\end{eqnarray}

