\label{_22}
\end{eqnarray}

Introduce following dynamic variables:

\begin{eqnarray}
equation \: 2\: (One electron spin dynamics notes)
\label{_22}
\end{eqnarray}

p.s. this definition of current	is not complete	as normally in magnetic case

\begin{eqnarray}
equation \: 3\: (One electron spin dynamics notes)
\label{_22}
\end{eqnarray}

should discuss it late.

Now following equations	of motion for the electronic charge, velocity (current) and spin densities can be obtained (T.Takabayasi, Prog. Theor.Phys., 19, 283 (1955). A set of these equations would make a corresponding basis of time dependent current density functional theory (TDCDFT), while charge and spin densities equations will define time dependent density functional theory (TDDFT).

\begin{eqnarray}
equation \: 4\: (One electron spin dynamics notes)
\label{_22}
\end{eqnarray}

Last equation means the equation of motion for the spin. In its right side, the first term is the classical torque exerted on the spin by the external magnetic field through the associated magnetic moment, while the second term implies that the spin is also subjected to the additional torque ("spin torque"), which is dependent on the gradient of the spin distribution itself, and tends to align neighborin spins parallel.

\subsubsection{Quantum torque}

Let us analyze this pure quantum torque.

\begin{eqnarray}
equation \: 5\: (One electron spin dynamics notes)
\label{_22}
\end{eqnarray}

The occurrence of means the action inside our fluid which tends to align the distribution of spin directions. A noticeable fact is that torque, is of similar form which have been introduced by Landau, in his phenomenological approach to magnetic dynamics (spin waves) in ferromagnetic media. It can thus be seen for a simple example that, as a consequence of that spin torque, we may have such solutions in this hydrodynamical theory as to behave like a spin wave.

However, there are several important differences. $equation$. We can present this torque in a form of standard Heisenberg pairwise interaction.

\begin{eqnarray}
equation \: 6\: (One electron spin dynamics notes)
\label{_22}
\end{eqnarray}

This torque is written for a single electron, and this pure quantum interaction represents ‘self-interaction’ or intraelectron interaction of electron spin density and its gradients or spin densities of a single electron at different points. On this stage in such hydrodynamic description it does not contain any standard interelectron exchange coupling terms at all. Thus the usage of term ‘exchange’ here is not quite appropriate as this interaction is related to non uniformity of a single electron density distribution due to quantum “self	stress”. Also, the introduction of spin pairwise Heisenberg like interaction can be done only approximately, as Pauli equation contains only quadratic gradients.

Thus in the dynamical EOM for a single electron

\begin{eqnarray}
equation \: 7\: (One electron spin dynamics notes)
\label{_22}
\end{eqnarray}

the first term in the right part corresponds to simple precession in the magnetic field (external or internal) with a clear classical analogue, second term has pure spin nature and represent quantum torque due to non uniformity spin density, while the third term represents charge-spin mixed torque which should be always important for the description of interaction of charge and z-component of spin density.

\subsubsection{Solution in some simple cases}
Assuming change and current density are stationary (first adiabatic approximation) and uniform. Taking into account the main feature of dynamical equations above that the quantum terms (stress) appear only in divergences (so Ehrenfest’s theorem holds) we can integrate the equation over whole space. All non linear quantum terms disappear and we obtain

\begin{eqnarray}
equation \: 8\: (One electron spin dynamics notes)
\label{_22}
\end{eqnarray}

which shows that the electron on the average moves like a classical particle and it can be described in this case using classical EOM without any operators. However, we should stress that this result holds for the integral over whole space. In solids, single electron density can be found beyond own atom WS cell and the corresponding integral over WS cell might not be sufficient for the Gauss theorem to hold.

