\subsubsection{Relaxation}

Let us start with usual EOM

\begin{eqnarray}
equation \: 19\: (One electron spin dynamics notes)
\label{_22}
\end{eqnarray}

$equation$

Where external field is still a source of dynamics and exchange correlation field now is no longer local and can be presented in general way (see Brownian Motion of a classical spin, A.Kawabata, Prog.Theor.Phys.,48,6B, 2237 (1972))

\begin{eqnarray}
equation \: 20\: (One electron spin dynamics notes)
\label{_22}
\end{eqnarray}

assuming slow variation in space and time we can instead present this field in gradients expansion

\begin{eqnarray}
equation \: 21\: (One electron spin dynamics notes)
\label{_22}
\end{eqnarray}

with

\begin{eqnarray}
equation \: 22\: (One electron spin dynamics notes)
\label{_22}
\end{eqnarray}

so the dynamic equation for one electron will take form

\begin{eqnarray}
equation \: 23\: (One electron spin dynamics notes)
\label{_22}
\end{eqnarray}

this is already EOM similar to phenomenological LL form. A shape of relaxation term is not unique and several other forms can be found in literature. No spin orbit coupling included.

The additional and very important term in relaxation comes from removal charge and current dynamics as magnetization is not an independent dynamic variable small memory from other electronic degrees of freedom is still present and should be taken into account.

We also stress that this equation contains gradients of spin and charge density everywhere in space and many of these terms cannot be called as exchange interelectron coupling as was already mentioned above.


\subsubsection{Introduction and discussion of currents.}

Let us now consider only spin current

\begin{eqnarray}
equation \: 24\: (One electron spin dynamics notes)
\label{_22}
\end{eqnarray}

So the EOM can be written as

\begin{eqnarray}
equation \: 25\: (One electron spin dynamics notes)
\label{_22}
\end{eqnarray}

As we saw above there are two contributions to electronic spin current.

\begin{eqnarray}
equation \: 26\: (One electron spin dynamics notes)
\label{_22}
\end{eqnarray}

there are two contributions to the spin current here. Both contributions related to non uniform	electronic spin density. First term in the right side cannot be presented in a torque form while the last term correspond to spin torque that tends to rotate the inhomogeneous spin density. All these terms do not relate to the exchange coupling torque determined by interelectron interaction as we consider one electron problem in local approximation.

The importance of these terms is huge in spin transport studies where charge spin gradients (imbalance) are large (contacts including magnetic-nonmagnetic contacts, electric field, lasers).

However, there is another contribution to the spin current, so called transport spin current, which is carried by an imbalance in the populations of the states near the Fermi level.


\subsubsection{Addition of spin orbit coupling.}

One of the most popular effect created by spin orbit coupling (there are several of them) is the addition of spin accumulation term as $equation$



\begin{eqnarray}
equation \: 27\: (One electron spin dynamics notes)
\label{_22}
\end{eqnarray}

This term leads to relaxation of any deviation of the FM spin density from its equilibrium value. Tau is spin-flip relaxation time. Non equilibrium spin density also can be obtained in linear response method.



\subsection{Spin dynamics in solids}
\subsection{Spin dynamics in Linear-Response regime}

Consider first average magnetization $\mathbf{m}\left( \mathbf{r},t\right) $
in the linear response framework
\begin{equation}
\delta \mathbf{m}\left( \mathbf{r},t\right) \triangleq \mathbf{m}\left( 
\mathbf{r},t\right) -m_{0}\left( \mathbf{r}\right) \mathbf{e}_{z}=\int 
\widehat{\chi }\left( \mathbf{r,r}^{\prime };t-t^{\prime }\right) \mathbf{B}
_{\text{xt}}\left( \mathbf{r}^{\prime },t^{\prime }\right) d\mathbf{r}
^{\prime }dt^{\prime }  \label{linrespm}
\end{equation}
where alternating with time inhomogeneous magnetic field is imposed upon an
equilibrium state with spontaneous magnetzation of value $m_{0}\left( 
\mathbf{r}\right) $ directed along $z$ - axis, $\widehat{\chi }\left( 
\mathbf{r,r}^{\prime };t-t^{\prime }\right) $ being the dynamic spin
susceptibility tensor given by Kubo formula
\begin{equation}
{}\widehat{\chi }_{ik}\left( \mathbf{r,r}^{\prime };t-t^{\prime }\right) =
\frac{i}{\hbar }\left\langle \left[ \mathfrak{m}_{i}\left( \mathbf{r}
,t\right) ,\mathfrak{m}_{k}\left( \mathbf{r}^{\prime },t^{\prime }\right) 
\right] \right\rangle .{}  \label{Kubokhi}
\end{equation}
In what follows we will use Fourier transform in time. Thus, the
spin-dynamics equation in the linear-response regime reads
\begin{equation}
\int \widehat{\chi }^{-1}\left( \mathbf{r,r}^{\prime };\omega \right) \delta 
\mathbf{m}\left( \mathbf{r}^{\prime },\omega \right) d\mathbf{r}^{\prime }=
\mathbf{B}_{\text{xt}}\left( \mathbf{r},\omega \right) .  \label{linsdeq}
\end{equation}

It is impossible to exactly calculate $\widehat{\chi}\left( \mathbf{r,r}
^{\prime};\omega\right) $ for many-electron system. We will use dynamical
self-consistent field approximation [synonim: random-phase approximation
(RPA)] that restores rotational invariance in spin space missed in static
self-consistent field (LSDF) approximation.


It is needless to recast the well-known derivation of RPA expression for $
\widehat{\chi }\left( \mathbf{r,r}^{\prime };\omega \right) $. Note only
that, for a collinear system, the longitudinal and transverse components of $
\widehat{\chi }\left( \mathbf{r,r}^{\prime };\omega \right) $ decouple from
each other. Since we are interested in the circular ($+-$) component, we
will omit the component indexes. We have in RPA
\begin{equation}
\widehat{\chi }^{-1}\left( \mathbf{r,r}^{\prime };\omega \right) =\widehat{
\chi }_{0}^{-1}\left( \mathbf{r,r}^{\prime };\omega \right) -2\frac{B_{\text{
xc}}^{0}\left( \mathbf{r}\right) }{m_{0}\left( \mathbf{r}\right) }\delta
\left( \mathbf{r}-\mathbf{r}^{\prime }\right)  \label{RPAkhi}
\end{equation}
where indexing by `0' means that respective quantity is calculated in LSDF
approximation at equilibrium. For example,


%=\sum \lim_{\mu ,\nu }\frac{f\left( \varepsilon _{\mu \uparrow }\right)-f\left( \varepsilon _{\nu \downarrow }\right)}{\varepsilon_{\nu\downarrow }-\varepsilon _{\mu \uparrow }+\hbar \omega +i0^{+}}m_{\mu \nu}^{+}\left( \mathbf{r}\right) m_{\nu \mu }^{-}\left( \mathbf{r}^{\prime}\right) ,

\begin{align}
\widehat{\chi }_{0}\left(\mathbf{r,r}^{\prime};\omega \right) & =\frac{i}{\hbar}\int_{0}^{\infty}\left\langle \left[ \mathfrak{m}^{+}\left( \mathbf{r},t\right) ,\mathfrak{m}^{-}\left( \mathbf{r}^{\prime }\right) \right]\right\rangle _{0}e^{-i\left( \omega -i0^{+}\right) t}dt  \notag \\
& =\lim_{\mu ,\nu }\frac{f\left( \varepsilon _{\mu \uparrow }\right)-f\left( \varepsilon _{\nu \downarrow }\right)}{\varepsilon_{\nu\downarrow }-\varepsilon _{\mu \uparrow }+\hbar \omega +i0^{+}}m_{\mu \nu}^{+}\left( \mathbf{r}\right) m_{\nu \mu }^{-}\left( \mathbf{r}^{\prime}\right) ,
\label{khi0}
\end{align}
where
\begin{equation}
m_{\mu \nu }^{\pm }=\psi _{\mu \uparrow ,\downarrow }^{\ast }\psi _{\nu
\downarrow ,\uparrow }  \label{mmdens}
\end{equation}
is the density of circular magnetic moment $\pm $ component between the band
states $\mu $ and $\nu $, $\psi _{\mu \sigma }\left( \mathbf{r}\right) $
being LSDF spin-polarized band wave functions. Let us make use of a
subsidiary identity following at $\mathbf{A}=0$ from Eq.(\ref{Schreq}).
Introducing also the magnetic moment current density between band states $
\mu $ and $\nu $ by
\begin{equation}
\mathbf{J}_{\mu \nu }^{\pm }=\frac{\hbar }{2mi}\left( \psi _{\mu \uparrow
,\downarrow }^{\ast }\mathbf{\nabla }\psi _{\nu \downarrow ,\uparrow }-\psi
_{\nu \downarrow ,\uparrow }\mathbf{\nabla }\psi _{\mu \uparrow ,\downarrow
}^{\ast }\right) ,  \label{mmcdens}
\end{equation}
we get for any space point
\begin{equation}
2B_{\text{xc}}^{0}m_{\mu \nu }^{\pm }=\left( \varepsilon _{\nu \downarrow
,\uparrow }-\varepsilon _{\mu \uparrow ,\downarrow }\right) m_{\mu \nu
}^{\pm }+i\hbar \mathbf{\nabla \cdot J}_{\mu \nu }^{\pm }\,.
\label{interim2}
\end{equation}
Thus we obtain after proper transformation

\begin{align}
2B_{\text{xc}}^{0}\left( \mathbf{r}\right) \widehat{\chi }_{0}\left( \mathbf{r,r}^{\prime };\omega \right) & =\sum\lim_{\mu ,\nu }\frac{f\left(\varepsilon _{\mu \uparrow }\right) -f\left( \varepsilon _{\nu \downarrow }\right) }{\varepsilon _{\nu \downarrow }-\varepsilon _{\mu \uparrow }+\hbar \omega +i0^{+}}\left( \varepsilon _{\nu \downarrow }-\varepsilon _{\mu \uparrow }\right) m_{\mu \nu }^{+}\left( \mathbf{r}\right) m_{\nu \mu }^{-}\left( \mathbf{r}^{\prime }\right)  \notag \\
+& i\hbar \sum\lim_{\mu ,\nu }\frac{f\left( \varepsilon _{\mu \uparrow}\right) -f\left( \varepsilon _{\nu \downarrow }\right) }{\varepsilon _{\nu \downarrow }-\varepsilon _{\mu \uparrow }+\hbar \omega +i0^{+}}\mathbf{\nabla \cdot J}_{\mu \nu }^{+}\left( \mathbf{r}\right) m_{\nu \mu }^{-}\left( \mathbf{r}^{\prime }\right) =  \notag \\
& m_{0}\left( \mathbf{r}\right) \delta \left( \mathbf{r}-\mathbf{r}^{\prime}\right) -\hbar \omega \widehat{\chi }_{0}\left( \mathbf{r,r}^{\prime};\omega \right) -\hbar \widehat{\Lambda }\left( \mathbf{r,r}^{\prime};\omega \right),
\label{interim1}
\end{align}
where
\begin{equation}
\widehat{\Lambda }\left( \mathbf{r,r}^{\prime };\omega \right) =\mathbf{
\nabla }_{\mathbf{r}}\mathbf{\cdot }\widehat{\mathbf{L}}\left( \mathbf{r,r}
^{\prime };\omega \right) ,\;\widehat{\mathbf{L}}\left( \mathbf{r,r}^{\prime
};\omega \right) \triangleq -i\sum\lim_{\mu ,\nu }\frac{f\left(
\varepsilon _{\mu \uparrow }\right) -f\left( \varepsilon _{\nu \downarrow
}\right) }{\varepsilon _{\nu \downarrow }-\varepsilon _{\mu \uparrow }+\hbar
\omega +i0^{+}}\mathbf{J}_{\mu \nu }^{+}\left( \mathbf{r}\right) m_{\nu \mu
}^{-}\left( \mathbf{r}^{\prime }\right) .  \label{Lambda}
\end{equation}
The kernels $\widehat{\chi }_{0}\left( \omega \right) $ and $\widehat{
\Lambda }\left( \omega \right) $ may be decomposed into a sum of real and
imaginary parts
\begin{equation*}
\widehat{\chi }_{0}\left( \omega \right) =\widehat{\chi }_{0\text{r}}\left(
\omega \right) +i\widehat{\chi }_{0\text{i}}\left( \omega \right) ,\,
\widehat{\Lambda }\left( \omega \right) =\widehat{\Lambda }_{\text{r}}\left(
\omega \right) +i\widehat{\Lambda }_{\text{i}}\left( \omega \right)
\end{equation*}
with 
\begin{align}
\widehat{\chi }_{0\text{r}}\left( \mathbf{r,r}^{\prime };\omega \right) &
=\sum\lim_{\mu ,\nu }\frac{f\left( \varepsilon _{\mu \uparrow }\right)
-f\left( \varepsilon _{\nu \downarrow }\right) }{\varepsilon _{\nu
\downarrow }-\varepsilon _{\mu \uparrow }+\hbar \omega }m_{\mu \nu
}^{+}\left( \mathbf{r}\right) m_{\nu \mu }^{-}\left( \mathbf{r}^{\prime
}\right)  \label{khi0real} \\
\widehat{\Lambda }_{\text{r}}\left( \mathbf{r,r}^{\prime };\omega \right) & =
\mathbf{\nabla }_{\mathbf{r}}\mathbf{\cdot }\widehat{\mathbf{L}}_{\text{r}
}\left( \mathbf{r,r}^{\prime };\omega \right) ,\;\widehat{\mathbf{L}}_{\text{
r}}\left( \mathbf{r,r}^{\prime };\omega \right) =-i\sum\lim_{\mu ,\nu }
\frac{f\left( \varepsilon _{\mu \uparrow }\right) -f\left( \varepsilon _{\nu
\downarrow }\right) }{\varepsilon _{\nu \downarrow }-\varepsilon _{\mu
\uparrow }+\hbar \omega }\mathbf{J}_{\mu \nu }^{+}\left( \mathbf{r}\right)
m_{\nu \mu }^{-}\left( \mathbf{r}^{\prime }\right)  \label{reLambda}
\end{align}
and
\begin{align}
\widehat{\chi }_{0\text{i}}\left( \mathbf{r,r}^{\prime };\omega \right) &
=\sum\lim_{\mu ,\nu }\pi \left[ f\left( \varepsilon _{\mu \uparrow
}-\hbar \omega \right) -f\left( \varepsilon _{\mu \uparrow }\right) \right]
\delta \left( \varepsilon _{\nu \downarrow }-\varepsilon _{\mu \uparrow
}+\hbar \omega \right) m_{\mu \nu }^{+}\left( \mathbf{r}\right) m_{\nu \mu
}^{-}\left( \mathbf{r}^{\prime }\right)  \label{khi0imag} \\
\widehat{\Lambda }_{\text{i}}\left( \mathbf{r,r}^{\prime };\omega \right) & =
\mathbf{\nabla }_{\mathbf{r}}\mathbf{\cdot }\widehat{\mathbf{L}}_{\text{i}%
}\left( \mathbf{r,r}^{\prime };\omega \right) ,\;  \notag \\
\widehat{\mathbf{L}}_{\text{i}}\left( \mathbf{r,r}^{\prime };\omega \right)
& =-i\sum\lim_{\mu ,\nu }\pi \left[ f\left( \varepsilon _{\mu \uparrow
}-\hbar \omega \right) -f\left( \varepsilon _{\mu \uparrow }\right) \right]
\delta \left( \varepsilon _{\nu \downarrow }-\varepsilon _{\mu \uparrow
}+\hbar \omega \right) \mathbf{J}_{\mu \nu }^{+}\left( \mathbf{r}\right)
m_{\nu \mu }^{-}\left( \mathbf{r}^{\prime }\right) .  \label{imLambda}
\end{align}
In symbolic form, Eq.(\ref{RPAkhi}) may be transformed with the use of Eq.(
\ref{interim1}) as follows
\begin{equation}
\widehat{\chi }\left( \omega \right) =\widehat{\chi }_{0}\left( \omega
\right) \left[ I-2\widehat{B}_{\text{xc}}^{0}\widehat{m}_{0}^{-1}\widehat{
\chi }_{0}\left( \omega \right) \right] ^{-1}=\hbar ^{-1}\left[ \omega +
\widehat{\Lambda }\left( \omega \right) \widehat{\chi }_{0}^{-1}\left(
\omega \right) \right] ^{-1}\widehat{m}_{0}.  \label{polRPAkhi}
\end{equation}

\textcolor{magenta}{[from  Vladimir's nots]}

\textcolor{Sepia}{At the moment the theory of linear response of TDDFT is
the only method that allows one to calculate the spin dynamics taking into account the
electron-magnon interaction in the case of a small magnetic field.}

\section{LR-TDDFT}
\subsection{Dynamic susceptibility}

SDF in solids are described by the imaginary part of the dynamic spin susceptibility tensor 

\begin{eqnarray}
\nonumber
\chi^{\alpha\beta}(\mathbf{r},\mathbf{r}',\mathbf{q},\omega)= -\frac{i}{\hbar}\sum_{\mathbf{R}}e^{-i\mathbf{q}\cdot\mathbf{R}} \\
\times\int_0^\infty dt\langle[\hat{s}_{\alpha}(\mathbf{r}+\mathbf{R},t),\hat{s}_{\beta}(\mathbf{r}')]\rangle e^{i(\omega+i\eta)t}.
\label{chi}
\end{eqnarray}

Here, $\alpha,\beta=x,y,z,0$ denote components of the tensor, $\mathbf{r}$ and $\mathbf{r}'$ are position vectors inside the crystal unit cell, $\mathbf{q}$ is the wavevector in the Brillouin zone, $\omega$ is the frequency, $\mathbf{R}$ is the lattice vector, $\langle...\rangle$ denotes the thermal and quantum-mechanical expectation value, $\eta\rightarrow 0^+$, and $\hat{s}_\alpha(\mathbf{r},t)$ is the density operator when $\alpha=0$, otherwise it is the $\alpha$ component of the spin density operator. For collinear magnetic states and in the absence of spin-orbit coupling, many of the tensor elements are zero. In particular, if one chooses the $z$ axis along the magnetization direction (or sublattice magnetization in the case of antiferromagnets), the susceptibility tensor in the matrix notation becomes


\begin{equation}
    \check{\chi}=\left(\begin{array}{cccc}
     \chi^{xx} & \chi^{xy} & 0         & 0         \\
    -\chi^{xy} & \chi^{xx} & 0         & 0         \\
      0        & 0         & \chi^{zz} & \chi^{0z} \\
      0        & 0         & \chi^{0z} & \chi^{00} \\
    \end{array}\right),
\label{mchi}
\end{equation}

where the dependence on  $\mathbf{r}$, $\mathbf{r}'$, $\mathbf{q}$, and $\omega$ variables is not shown explicitly. It is convenient to express the transverse components ($\chi^{xx}$ and $\chi^{xy}$) in terms of the circular susceptibilities

\begin{eqnarray}
\chi^{+-}=2\left(\chi^{xx}-i\chi^{xy}\right) \\
\chi^{-+}=2\left(\chi^{xx}+i\chi^{xy}\right).
\label{chicirc}
\end{eqnarray}


Note that the transverse components are decoupled from the longitudinal susceptibility ($\chi^{zz}$). On the other hand, $\chi^{zz}$ is coupled to the density response ($\chi^{00}$) through the  spin-density susceptibility function $\chi^{0z}$. 

\textcolor{magenta}{[from Alex article]}

\subsection{Number of SDF}

For SDF analysis, it is often not necessary to resolve intra-atomic fluctuations. Therefore, for each nonequivalent atom it is convenient to introduce the SDF spectral function 

\begin{equation}
A^{\alpha\beta}(\mathbf{q},\omega)= -\frac{\hbar}{\pi}\int d\mathbf{r}\int d\mathbf{r}^\prime\ \text{Im}\chi^{\alpha\beta}(\mathbf{r},\mathbf{r} ^{\prime},\mathbf{q},\omega),
\label{ASDF}
\end{equation} 

where $\mathbf{r}$ and $\mathbf{r}'$ variables are integrated over the atomic sphere. Correspondingly, the density of on-site SDF can be defined by integrating $A^{\alpha\beta}(\mathbf{q},\omega)$ over the BZ.

\begin{equation}
N^{\alpha\beta}(\omega)=\frac{1}{\Omega_{\text{BZ}}}\int_{\Omega_{\text{BZ}}}d\mathbf{q} A^{\alpha\beta}(\mathbf{q},\omega). 
\label{NSDF}
\end{equation} 

where $\Omega_{\text{BZ}}$ is the BZ volume. In order to better analyze the distribution of SDF in the BZ, one can also consider the partial-$\mathbf{q}$ density of on-site SDF defined as

\begin{equation}
N_{\Omega_{\mathbf{q}}}^{\alpha\beta}(\omega)=\frac{1}{\Omega_{\text{BZ}}}\int_{\Omega_{\mathbf{q}}}d\mathbf{q} A^{\alpha\beta}(\mathbf{q},\omega). 
\label{NrSDF}
\end{equation} 

Here, the integration is over a $\Gamma$-point-centered sphere with the volume $\Omega_{\mathbf{q}}$ ($\Omega_{\mathbf{q}}<\Omega_{\text{BZ}}$). Further, we introduce the on-site number of transverse SDF $n^t(\omega)$ as well as longitudinal SDF $n^l(\omega)$,

\begin{eqnarray}
n^t(\omega) =\frac{1}{2}\int_{0}^{\omega }d\omega'\left[N^{+-}(\omega')+N^{-+}(\omega')\right] \\
\label{ntSDF}
n^l(\omega) =\int_{0}^{\omega }d\omega' N^{zz}(\omega').
\label{nlSDF}
\end{eqnarray}

\textcolor{magenta}{[from Alex article]}

\subsection{FDT. On-site spin correlator}


FDT plays a crucial role in the physics of SDF since it allows to find a number of useful properties that characterize the SDF spectrum. In particular, it can be used to evaluate SC which is defined as an energy integral of the dynamic on-site connected spin correlation function and is an important measure of the strength of SDF in solids. According to FDT, the transverse and longitudinal contributions to the SC are given by

\begin{eqnarray}
\left\langle\mathbf{s}^{2}\right\rangle^t_\omega =\frac{1}{2}\int _{0}^{\omega }d\omega'\coth{(\beta\omega'/2)} \\
\times\left[N^{+-}(\omega')+N^{-+}(\omega')\right],
\label{SCt}
\end{eqnarray}

and

\begin{eqnarray}
\left\langle\mathbf{s}^{2}\right\rangle^l_\omega =\int _{0}^{\omega }d\omega'\coth{(\beta\omega'/2)}N^{zz}(\omega'),
\label{SCl}
\end{eqnarray}
 
respectively. Note that since SC is defined as a connected correlation function, the longitudinal contribution doesn't contain the term proportional to the equilibrium local moment. At T=0, SDF originate purely from the spin zero-point motion and we have $\left\langle\mathbf{s}^{2}\right\rangle^{t,l}_\omega=n^{t,l}(\omega)$. Therefore, the spin zero-point motion contribution to the SC is given by $n^{t,l}(\omega)$. SC is related to the effective fluctuating moment that is given by

\begin{equation}
m_{\text{eff}}(\omega)=\sqrt{\left(m_{\text{eff}}^{t}(\omega)\right)^2+\left(m_{\text{eff}}^{l}(\omega)\right)^2}.
\label{meff}
\end{equation}
 
Here, transverse and longitudinal contributions to $m_{\text{eff}}(\omega)$ are given by

\begin{equation}
m_{\text{eff}}^{t,l}(\omega)=\frac{g\mu_B}{\hbar}\sqrt{\left\langle\mathbf{s}^{2}\right\rangle^{t,l}_\omega},
\label{mtleff}
\end{equation}

where $g$ is the electron g-factor and $\mu_B$ is the Bohr magneton. Note that according to the above equations, the evaluation of the full ($\omega\rightarrow\infty$) values  of SC and the effective fluctuating moment involves integrals over all ranges of $\mathbf{q}$'s and $\omega$'s which makes such studies computationally demanding.

FDT can be also used to evaluate the value of the equilibrium local moment $m\equiv g\mu_B\int d\mathbf{r}\langle \hat{s}_z(\mathbf{r})\rangle$ (the spatial integration is over the atomic sphere). This leads to the following sum rule:

\begin{eqnarray}
m=m_{\text{a}}(\omega\rightarrow\infty),
\label{SumRuleEq}
\end{eqnarray}

where we defined an auxilary function 

\begin{equation}
m_{\text{a}}(\omega)=\frac{g\mu_B}{4\hbar^2}\int_0^\omega d\omega'\left[N^{+-}(\omega')-N^{-+}(\omega')\right].
\label{m0omega}
\end{equation}

\textcolor{magenta}{[from Alex article]}


